    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Paris.</placeName>
                    <date>Dec. 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1874</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental">To Charles Darwin E<hi rend="superscript">sq</hi>. | Down. Beckenham. Kent</seg>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>We had the honor to send you this morning by book-post the first copy, which ready, of the french translation of your “Naturalist’s journey on board of the Beagle,” which will be published in a few days here.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> We hope that the translation of Mr Barbier’s as well as the typographical part of the book will merit your approbation. The french press will soon give some reports on our translation, which we dare say, has really been impatiently waited for since of a few months.</p>
<p>According to our proposal of May 14. 1873. a percentage in the sale of the book 〈is〉 due to you, as soon as it will have reach〈ed〉 750 copies. This percentage has been fixed at £20.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> —and we hope to be soon able to hand you the said sum.</p>
<p>We remain, Dear Sir, | yours most obediently | C Reinwald &amp; Co</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Reinwald refers to Barbier trans. 1875, a French translation by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_272.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edmond Barbier</ref> of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4255.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Journal of researches</hi> (1870)</ref>. CD’s copy is in the Darwin Library–Down.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 21, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8911.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C.-F. Reinwald, 14 May 1873</ref>. CD recorded a payment of £20 from Reinwald on 26 February 1875 in his Account books–banking account (Down House MS).</note>
        </div>        
            
